{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2374"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.1,0.8,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1311"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-month history of severe headaches. They have been present more days than not and are progressively getting more severe. There are no apparent triggers or preceding aura. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her BMI is 32 kg/m\u00b2. There are no abnormal findings on physical examination apart from bilateral swelling of the optic nerve heads found on fundoscopy. Visual acuity is normal. CT reveals no abnormalities and opening pressure on lumbar puncture is 40 cmH\u2082O (10-25).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cluster headache","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Space-occupying lesion","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is typically found in young, overweight women. Pathogenesis is unclear and an area of active research. The history of progressive headaches is characteristic, and symptoms may also include transient visual phenomena (darkening, blurring, or horizontal diplopia), pulsatile tinnitus, dizziness, and neck/back pain. Diagnosis is supported by papilloedema on fundoscopy, which suggests raised intracranial pressure, and confirmed by elevated opening pressure on lumbar puncture. A lumbar puncture can safely be performed so long as no alternative aetiology is found on other investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with headache and papilloedema due to impaired venous drainage and increased intracranial pressure. However, it typically has a more acute onset over days to weeks rather than months, is often associated with focal neurological deficits or seizures, and would show venous filling defects on contrast-enhanced CT or MR venography. Risk factors include oral contraceptive use, pregnancy, thrombophilia, and dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espace-occupying lesion\u003C/strong\u003E such as a brain tumour or abscess would likely be identified on CT, however this patient would require an MRI to confidently rule this out. Space-occupying lesions typically cause progressive neurological symptoms including focal deficits, personality changes, or seizures in addition to headaches. The normal CT scan makes this diagnosis less likely, though small lesions could have be missed without MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E causes sudden-onset headache that is typically excruciating (i.e. the classical \u0022thunderclap\u0022 headache). It is usually associated with acute neurological deficits, neck stiffness, photophobia, and altered consciousness. The gradual onset over months in this case makes subarachnoid haemorrhage highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are episodic, unilateral headaches that occur in clusters over weeks to months, followed by remission periods. They are typically brief (15 minutes to 3 hours), extremely painful, and associated with ipsilateral autonomic features such as lacrimation, nasal congestion, and Horner\u0027s syndrome. They are not associated with features of raised intracranial pressure such as papilloedema, and the chronic progressive nature described here is inconsistent with cluster headaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The finding of papilloedema requires prompt investigation to determine the underlying cause of the raised intracranial pressure.","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension typically affects young women with obesity and presents with chronic headaches and papilloedema.","Elevated opening pressure on lumbar puncture with normal neuroimaging is diagnostic of idiopathic intracranial hypertension."],"references":["Wall M. Update on Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension. Neurol Clin. 2017 Feb;35(1):45-57.","Wakerley BR, Mollan SP, Sinclair AJ. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension: Update on diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):384-388. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0232. PMID: 32675143; PMCID: PMC7385768."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2374"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:40:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:40:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na